One of our favourite photos from pli.panda featuring the 41 round salute fired in front of #TowerBridge in tribute and to mark the passing of #PrincePhilip 🙏🏼 One round was fired every minute from midday on 10th April by members of the Honourable Artillery company. All 3 guns were fired in unison every sixty seconds with this act replicated out at sea on Royal Navy boats, and with other army units in Belfast, Cardiff, Edinburgh and beyond.

Wishing RoyalAlbertHall a happy 150th birthday with these cracking shots from steven.maddison! 🔥🥳 It’s 150 years since the great village hall opened, which actually came to exist because of Prince Albert’s passion for the arts, science and the wonders of industry from around the world which he displayed in 1851’s #GreatExhibition in Hyde Park in a huge world fair. The proceeds were then used to buy up land in #SouthKensington and he was able to build an arts and scientific quarter in London - now home to the Royal Albert Hall, but also Natural History Museum, Science Museum, the V&A, and Imperial College. Tickets for the Royal Albert Hall were sold to raise money for construction with the first 20 tickets bought by Queen Victoria which still make up the royal box to this day! 👑 Personally, we can’t wait for the bounce back! 💪🏼❤️ This hall has so many incredible stories and moments hidden in its walls. Some of our happiest London moments have been in this hall from Cirque du Soleil, Star Wars with the London Symphony Orchestra, The Proms, Cinderella with the English National Ballet, to Arctic Monkeys and more... so happy birthday RAH! And see you soon! 🥰🙌🏼

#LondonHistory | MrLondon on #SicilianAvenue in #Bloomsbury! 🇮🇹 The street was designed by architect Robert Worley in 1906 (completed in 1910) in a monumental Edwardian style, using Italian marble throughout, with colonnades and turrets. Ionic columns on plinths carry the street name in gold characters at both the eastern and western entrances of the avenue. ✨ Wonder Woman 2017 has a film 🎥 scene here as does The Guernsey Literary and Potato Peel Pie Society filmed in 2018. 🙌🏼 Who digs this little corner of London?! 👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼

Incredible photos of #KingsCross by griffie.visuals! 🔥📸❤️ The Western Concourse is the largest single-span structure in Europe, and was actually inspired by Victoria glasshouses like Kew Gardens, and designed to give passengers an uplifting experience before embarking on their journey. The £547M conversion of the station had to factor in all of its Grade I structures, be triple the size, whilst not placing additional load on the Grade I structures, and had to be ready on time for the 2012 olympics, and not cause a single delay to a train departure or arrival. They nailed it. Pretty incredible huh?! 🤷🏻‍♂️😱🥰🥳💪🏼

What a stunning part of the city! 🇬🇧❤️🇬🇧

MrLondon & Alice.Sampo show you why the 🇯🇵 Japanese Soufflé Pancake 🇯🇵 is by far, the most superior pancake you’ll ever make! 😱 TAG someone who needs this recipe in their life! 👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼
_______________________________________
INGREDIENTS FOR 4-5 PANCAKES 🥞 • 4 EGGS
• 70 GRAMS FLOUR
• 1 TABLESPOON OIL (to grease pan)
• 50 GRAMS SUGAR
• 4 TABLESPOON MILK
• 2 TEASPOONS VANILLA EXTRACT
• 1 TEASPOON BAKING POWDER
• 2 PINCHES OF SALT
_______________________________________
METHOD • First separate the egg whites and the yolks and beat the yolks.
• Add the milk to the yolks along with the vanilla extract. Mix until frothy.
• Sieve the flour and baking powder together, and add to mix.
• Add a couple of pinches of salt. Mix until combined but don’t over mix.
• Preheat a pan on a LOW heat. Meanwhile whisk the egg whites until frothy.
• Add the sugar to the egg whites a little at a time and beat until hard peaks form.
• Now add 1/3 of the egg white mix to the yolk mix and stir in slowly until all the same colour.
• Now put the yolk mix back into the rest of the egg white mix and mix with folded motions, trying not to break the air bubbles.
• Grease your pan with a little oil and pour 3 tablespoons of your mix, per pancake.
• Cover the pan and cook for 2 minutes. After 2 minutes, add another 2 tablespoons of the mix to each of your pancakes. Cover again.
• Cook for another 4 minutes, and then very carefully turn the pancakes over, and cook for a further 4 minutes, covering the pan again.
• The pancakes are done – add your favourite toppings to taste. We sieve powdered royal icing sugar over the top and add fruits such as blueberries, strawberries, clotted cream OR extra thick cream, and Golden Syrup. But feel free to freestyle!

#LondonHistory  MrLondon in #Mayfair... #MountStreet looks positively resplendent, as always. 🥰 This street was entirely rebuilt in the late 1800’s to the ‘Queen Anne’ way of doing things... in other words to permit individualism without altogether abandoning regularity, in order to make it the gayest street in Mayfair. 😍 
___________________________________________
Swipe and you’ll see the #CoachAndHorses pub on Bruton Street which is currently boarded up until the pubs to reopen. 😢 Have to admit it felt sad seeing it like this. This is one of Mayfair’s oldest surviving #Tudor taverns, literally synonymous with horse drawn carriages that ran the city in the late 1700’s, before the railway systems were built. Can’t wait for life to return to normal and hope you enjoy a little history. 🇬🇧❤️🇬🇧

MrLondon on #ShadThames... definitely one of my favourite streets in London... in the late 1800’s these bridges connected the old riverside buildings to the storehouses and mills, so clippers (small cargo ships) could unload their cargo such as spices, dried fruit, teas, coffee etc - this area was quite literally known as the ‘larder of London’. Over time to city moved to containers which were unloaded further east, so by the 1970’s this whole area transitioned to residential and now feature expensive apartments, cafes, bars and restaurants. But it’s still a treat to walk under these bridges and soak the history up! And it’s right next to Tower Bridge. So great location for this history trip. 👌🏼

MrLondon on Southwark Street - the Grade II Listed building on the left is known as the “Hop Exchange” - Hops are obviously used in the brewing industry and they would be harvested from farms & "hop gardens" in places like Kent in the 19th century and then brought by railway to #LondonBridge Station, or by boat up the River #Thames. They were then stored in the many warehouses in the #Borough area and the Hop Exchange was a single market centre for dealers in hops. Its glass roof allowed business on the trading floor of the Great Hall to be conducted under natural light. 👌🏼 I’ve always loved the architecture of its facade and how it leads your eyes towards the #Shard 👀 It’s also got seriously convenient parking opposite if you’re ever going to #BoroughMarket! 💪🏼

🚁 JasonHawkes flying over #BatterseaPowerStation! 📸🔥 Hell of a view! Remember when this was just abandoned wasteland?! The original coal fired power station was closed in the ‘70’s and completely decommissioned in the ‘80’s. Energy supply had shifted away from coal. The government then made it Grade II listed (protected landmark or building) and the land would then be bought and sold multiple times. 🤦🏻‍♂️ There were rumours of it becoming a theme park. A football ground for Chelsea FC. Even a church. 😳 It was then acquired by a developer to build a whole new neighbourhood but that developer went bankrupt. 🤦🏻‍♂️😆 So decades went by. But eventually the British government brokered some (A LOT - £9BN) Malaysian investment and a whole new quarter for London was imagined! 🎉 The original power station was retained, each chimney taken down brick by brick, and restored and rebuilt to its former glory, and it is now set to become the new Apple 🍏 headquarters! 😱  The largest brick building in Europe is the centre piece to a completely new neighbourhood and will be with us for decades to come, but now, surrounded by culture and people. What a journey! 🙌🏼🙏🏼 // mrlondon

🎉🔥💪🏼 ANNDD WE’RE BACK! 💪🏼🔥🎉 MrLondon checking in... finally... after having my phone stolen on #OxfordStreet last Friday whilst taking photos of the Christmas lights. 🤦🏻‍♂️🤦🏻‍♂️ Luckily not hurt. I’ve learned the hard way that this is sadly happening across our city, especially around Oxford St, Regent St, Covent Garden, Soho etc. I’m not here to be an anti-PR machine as we head into Christmas. I just want people to be aware and safe. People just need to be wise to the fact there are organised gangs on mopeds and bikes, and they know that we’re all stopping to gawp at the Christmas lights, so they come from behind on their bikes and snatch your phone and BOOM... they’re gone. 😭 We all rely on our phones so much, so it’s worth being safe on the streets, and also taking time to check that your photos and docs are all backed up, because if you lose your memories it’s a pretty painful experience. So use things like iCloud or backup to your PC etc. 👌🏼 Also think about your two-factor authentication for Instagram and have it set up to a different number than the one being stolen (theoretically)... or you will get locked out like I did. 🙈🤦🏻‍♂️ I have a spare PayAsYouGo phone / SIM for this purpose now so I can get back online quicker and faster. Oh and if it happens, which I hope it won’t, call your network provider - ask a police officer if needs be - to block the SIM to the phone. 📸 AND for photography, whether with a camera or phone, have a friend watch over you whilst you’re taking pics. I’ve got so many messages from people who’ve had the same thing happen. So many phones. And a few with expensive cameras. So we all need to be alert. I was the 9th person in 1 HOUR to get caught in the same spot opposite Selfridges. BE AWARE. STAY SAFE. ❤️❤️❤️

Tips for Grinding Coffee: 
• Weigh an 18g shot of coffee and make an espresso - time it - you’re aiming for a 28-32s pour and the espresso should weigh 36g after extraction giving a 1:2 ratio. If the espresso doesn’t pour quick enough, your grind is too fine. If the espresso pours too quick, your grind is too coarse. 🙌🏼

belleannee with art news! 🖼  Better late than never. RoyalAcademyArts “Summer” Exhibition opens TOMORROW & marks the first time in RA’s 252 years that the Summer Exhibition has been postponed until autumn. 😱 (Note that it has never been cancelled! Think of what has happened beyond the gates over those years!). 🙌🏼 It also marks the first time two women have co-coordinated the exhibit. 💪🏼 This year there are tons of poignant works dealing with topics of the day - and there are also many minority and under-represented artists on show. And there are some heavy hitters that fall into all three of those categories which is super cool. Shortly after you enter, have a look for the Zanele Muholi portrait. Zanele is fascinating and is worth looking up. Also note the Njideka Crosby piece - and if you haven’t seen “The Price of Everything”, look that up too (ugh, sorry, I sound like my mom). 😆 Toward the middle to end spend time with the Ai Wei Wei urns - really look at the story he is telling. (Disclosure, he is guest number 1 at my imaginary dinner party) ◻️

Now, onto the photos I included The first is an assemblage of photographs by Isaac Julien RA taken 35 years ago but that could have been taken yesterday. Spend time with those. ◻️ Next shot is someone very important doing an interview. Then the small portraits by Anne-Marie Butlin. I know that I did not take a great photo but look closely - how can someone create that kind of life with a paint brush and tubes of color? Amazing. ◻️ I think that the woman’s trousers match that big column, don’t they? ☺️ Also - loving those colourful pieces in the background by Joe Tilton RA ◻️ Sneak peek at the Ai Wei Wei urns (mmmmm, & a flat Mercedes behind them). ◻️ & I missed that really cool wave picture / painting / drawing at the top of this photo & now I can’t zoom in on the number to tell you anything about it but isn’t it amazing how you can totally miss something the first time but then it calls to you? 🙌🏼 *sigh* I love art. ❤️ I wish I’d have been born a Saatchi. ◻️ Also the weird wiener thing can be yours for £1200. Go ahead, I won’t fight you for it this time. ◻️

The cafe opens at 11 in sweet temporary dig! ☕

MrLondon on #BerwickStreet ... Yesterday marked the 25th Anniversary of a defining album. If you were into Britpop and Indie in the 90’s you would have probably fallen into one of 2 camps. #Blur or #Oasis. 🇬🇧🎸🙌🏼 It was a battle of the ages, and in my case, at school growing up, friendship groups were literally defined by which camp you were in, and that in turn defined how you dressed.  Oasis album #WhatsTheStoryMorningGlory is for me *the* soundtrack of my youth. I can and do sing it cover to cover, still. But it was only later in life I realised the cover was shot on Berwick Street in #Soho. So I asked RonTimehin to help me shoot this line up of the album on the very same street back in 2017. 📸🔥👌🏼 it’s a great shot, some might say. //

We’ve got some good news about #BigBen! Over the next 6 weeks the scaffolding hiding the top of the #ElizabethTower which houses Big Ben 🔔 will gradually be taken down! 😱 Once revealed you’ll be able to see the famous tower in its brand new condition of restoration complete with 3,433 cast iron roof tiles which were removed and repaired in a specialist workshop. 👌🏼 Crumbling stone work and leaks were also fixed as part of the conservation work which has kept us all waiting for several years! 😭 But finally, some good news and we’ll be so glad to lay our eyes on the tower once more! 🤩 Work will continue lower down on the tower so it’s a semi-reveal. But it’s a great start! Enjoy! And thanks to andresbalcazar_ for this epic sunset shot! 🌅 🌇

What a week we’ve had with the new #RollsRoyceGhost! We been filming some stunning content around this mind-blowing car but we couldn’t wait for all the cinematic stuff to be cut, so in the meantime, here’s a behind-the-scenes of the global launch at Rolls-Royce HQ in #Goodwood. 💪🏼 We’ve definitely had worse days! 😆💪🏼🔥 In all honestly, Rolls-Royce release new cars so infrequently, it’s always an honour to be invited for such a moment as this. They design their cars to sell for 10-15 years, unlike many manufacturers who drop a new face-lift model every year. 👏🏼 So the arrival of any new Rolls-Royce is a moment and the automotive world sits up, every time. It’s a moment to savour and is always mixed with invention, ingenuity, science, patented technologies, world-first, mind-blowing features, and quite frankly it re-defines luxury for the next era... in this instance, moving us into a period of “post-opulence” and away from in-your-face bling... ✨ This means having all the technology at hand, but not in your face. Simplicity, not complexity. The car doing the work for you, ahead of when you need it. Let us know what you think! 👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼🤩🤩🤩

🎥 MrLondon discovering a film location for Guy Ritchie’s #LockStockAndTwoSmokingBarrels shot in 1998. He used these two buildings on Park Street at #BoroughMarket to house the two rival gangs. If you remember the scene our favourite cockney gang have just got off the blower with big-time gangster ‘Hatchet’ Harry Lonsdale to tell him they have raised the £100,000 necessary to take part in one of his high-stakes card games. They return to their grotty hideout and listen in on a rival gang carrying out a drug deal next door. ☺️👌🏼 Average house prices in 1998 were just under £200,000, but are now up at an eye watering £700,000+ 😭 Check it out next time you’re at thegentlemenbaristas for coffee! ☕️❤️☕️

clerkenwellboyec1 with a *free* exhibition recommendation... Internationally renowned artist, Ai Weiwei aiww has taken over IWM London’s iconic atrium with a new artwork: HISTORY OF BOMBS 🙏🏼💣💔
.
We visited on 15th August which marked 75 years since the end of World War II 🕊️
.
Tread carefully over 50 lifesize missiles and bombs. Exploring international migration, conflict as a root cause of human flow, and the relationship between the individual, society and the state, History of Bombs draws on the artist’s ongoing investigation into politics and power. 
.
From 24th September: Also taking place at imperialwarmuseums next month, “REFUGEES” explores the experiences of refugees throughout history and the ongoing issues faced by those affected.
.
Collectively, 17.5 million people have fled Afghanistan, Iraq, Libya, South Sudan, Syria and Yemen alone, due to recent conflict. IWM’s Refugees season will unlock the personal stories of people forced to flee their homes and those who work to support them. 
.
Entry is free, although you need to pre-book a time slot via the imperialwarmuseums website. There's also a haunting Holocaust Exhibition which again, is a must see.
.
Highly recommend a visit (we also booked a socially distanced guided tour which was extremely informative, heartbreaking 💔 and thought provoking) 🙏🏼🇬🇧🏰
.
My key takeaway: Very heartbreaking... but also extremely educational. We must understand our history, face up to the current atrocities of the world we live in, and learn from our past mistakes, in order to build a better future for the generations to come. Be kind and help others 🙏🏼
.

MrLondon passing through libertylondon over the weekend. Never been more grateful for a wide angle camera lens on our modern day smartphones! 📸😜 How gorgeous is the timber structure of Liberty? 🤷🏻‍♂️ It was built in 1875 (145 years ago). Half of the building on Regent St was acquired by Arthur Lasenby Liberty for a £2,000 loan from his future father-in-law. After 18 months he’d repaid the loan and acquired the second half of the building. In years to come adjacent properties were acquired also to make it what it is today. I’ve always loved the building. Who else loves it? 👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼

MrLondon checking in... today I’m featuring the beautiful illustrative work of my uncle JohnAlbanyHoyle who is insanely gifted! 😱👌🏼 I remember back when I was young, he would occasionally draw a concept car from scratch and post it to me. Fond memories! 🤗 Lately I’ve been loving his sketchbook illustrations which he colours digitally. This sketch features the #Gherkin and #StAndrewUndershaft church which is a pretty rare example of a church that managed to survive the Great Fire of London in 1666, and the Blitz in 1940/41. In the great fire 87 churches were lost including the original St Paul’s Cathedral, which makes the survival of St Andrew pretty special. Hope you like it! Follow johnalbanyhoyle for more. 🖼

rafredarrows & patrouilledefrance perform a Flypast yesterday to commemorate the 80th anniversary of Charles de Gaulle's BBC broadcast in 1940. emmanuelmacron was in London yesterday and said “This is where de Gaulle was able to form the first ranks of the French army which would go on fighting. The soldiers of London. This is where de Gaulle was able to call on the French people to join the resistance. The soldiers of the shadows. Because 80 years ago today, on June 18 1940, the United Kingdom gave Free France its first weapon, a BBC microphone. So the airwaves carried de Gaulle's determined words and spirit of resistance, which built a bridge across the Channel for those refusing to be enslaved or give up their freedom." 🇬🇧❤️🇫🇷

The #NeasdenTemple - or BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir London. In 2000 it held the Guinness World record for being the biggest Hindu temple outside of India - and it’s here in London. It’s built out of 2,828 tonnes of Bulgarian limestone and 2,000 tonnes of Italian marble. Built in 1992 and inaugurated in 1995. 🎥 MrLondon

UnitLondon online exhibition #DrawnTogether is now open and available to view online - TheUnitLDN.com - with the work of over 100 artists on sale to raise funds for WorldVisionUK and MSF “Doctors Without Borders” to help with their collective #COVID19 response for vulnerable communities and refugees in more than 70 countries. ❤️

Do take a look. ❤️🖼🎨 ____________________________________

An original film from the best dancers in the UK, to capture the mood of the nation during lockdown. 
________________________________
Set to an original piece of music the short encourages all artists to keep at it - “We need you. The world needs you.” says Royal Ballet principal dancer acampbell_1. The film explores the range of evolving emotions we are all feeling whilst being stuck at home. But their collective belief is that dance can exceed spoken word in its ability to tell the story and truly express the emotions. ❤️ We can’t wait for them all to return to stages across London in the future, but for now, please share this with anyone who loves dance and with anyone who relates to the piece... we suspect, quite a lot of us. 🙏🏼❤️

#BlackLivesMatter | This evening we’re sharing the work of MisanHarriman & RonTimehin - powerful photos taken from the protests over the past week. 📸🔥🖤 A full set of their images will be posted to our story tonight. Thanks for sharing guys. ❤️
____________________________________
London is a city encompassing more than 270 nationalities and 300 languages and at these protests, people of every nationality and skin colour stood shoulder-to-shoulder in solidarity to declare that Black Lives Matter - because for centuries, they haven’t. And as recently as May 25th - when George Floyd was brutally murdered in a 21st century lynching - his life didn’t matter to those white policemen. 😔 That senseless violence proved to be the straw that broke the camels back and the world has stood up and said “enough is enough”. 🤷🏻‍♂️ It’s a beautiful thing to watch London’s community in action. People laid aside their own problems, the challenges their own nations are facing, the problems within their own cultures and families, to lift up a community in incomprehensible amounts of pain. This has been their time to be heard, understood and supported. And we can only pray that the momentum of this movement will translate into deep and wide-spread societal change, here in the UK, and all around the world. ❤️🖤❤️
____________________________________
We believe that all lives should matter. But we acknowledge they don’t. There is inequality. There is persecution. There is injustice. We cannot pretend that systemic racism doesn’t exist.  And we cannot ignore the first-hand experiences of our black friends and their families, and the trauma they are experiencing during this season - they’ve spent years trying to forget these experiences, and now they’ve come flooding back. 🤷🏻‍♂️💔 _________
This has quickly become a world-wide anti-racist movement and the conversations we’re having now have been needed for a long time. We simply need your YES & AMEN! This isn’t a competition for who’s suffering the most. We’re not forgetting that other people have needs. We’re just focusing on one group of people rightg now, and we need all your love, all your empathy & all your compassion. ❤️

🖤 #Westminster - #BlackLivesMatter 🖤

🇬🇧 The Sounds of #CoventGarden by MrLondon... 🇬🇧 Me and alice.sampo took a walk to pick up some food. We came through the market in Covent Garden and it was surreal. It wasn’t quite apocalyptic, it was very peaceful, but in a slightly eerie way that 5PM on a Friday night shouldn’t be. 😳 No clinking of glasses and indistinct chatter. No buskers or performers in the square. No violinists or operatic singers under the neo-classical roof. 😔 So I decided to dive into my archive and pull out a few sound samples that remind me of the good times. And well, this is what I came up with. ☺️🙏🏼❤️

MrLondon with a little history... It’s 1968. Beatles “Lady Madonna” is Number 1. Protests ring out around London against the Vietnam War. And RAF Veteran pilot Alan Pollock is angry at defence cuts and that his beloved RAF aren’t marking their 50th anniversary with a fly-by in London. So Alan decided to take matters into his own hands, and whilst flying from Sussex to Norfolk he fakes radio problems and taps out a message to his commanders saying he’s lost visual sight of his 3 comrades and will make his own way back. 😳 Using just an AA map as a guide, he drops to 150ft below commercial aviation traffic, flies over Whitehall, dips his wings over the RAF Memorial in tribute, and then drops down to the Thames. Travelling at a speed of 300mph the #TowerBridge was quickly upon him and he makes a split second decision to fly THROUGH IT rather than over it, remembering at the last second he had a tail fin behind his head, which nearly catches the underside of the bridge! 😱 Alan’s opinion was that it’s in the Air Force’s blood to celebrate in the air - not on the ground. Parades were not befitting in his view. 🤷🏻‍♂️🤣 A cyclist fell off his bike and tore his trousers. Thankfully no-one was hurt. Alan called his wife’s mother and gave them a heads up - “there might be a bit of trouble - but not to worry”. He said. Alan after receiving widespread support from across the RAF was spared an official court martial and instead “retired on medical grounds”, probably to deny him the chance to complain about the defence cuts. Looking back at 82 Alan said he had no regrets. ☺️🤷🏻‍♂️🤣

A Creamy store cupboard PASTA with crispy bread crumbs and rosemary that doesn’t use butter, eggs or cream! 
Serves 2-3 (you can keep any pasta sauce in the fridge for later)
_________________________________________________

RECIPE 
Pasta sauce
2 garlic cloves, roughly chopped
Olive oil
1 can cannellini beans (bean water reserved)
1 heaped tsp Dijon mustard
Squeeze of lemon juice or 1 tsp white wine/cider vinegar
Handful grated parmesan (optional, if available)
The rest
Roughly 70g dried pasta per person
1 tbsp breadcrumbs per person *see note.
Handful rosemary leaves
Olive oil
Salt and pepper
____________________________________________________ 
METHOD 
1. Place 2 tbsp olive oil in a saucepan over a low heat. Add the garlic & cook until it has softened (about 3-4 mins). 2. Making sure you keep the water drain the cannellini beans. Add the beans to your blender of choice (nutribullet, blender, magimix or use a stick blender). 3. Add the mustard followed by 3tbsp of the reserved bean water. Then add the garlic & any garlic cooking oil & a further 3 tbsp of olive oil. If you have any fresh cheese or lemon juice add this now. Otherwise add 1 tsp white wine or cider vinegar. 
4. Blend until smooth. Taste for seasoning. You’ll probably need a good pinch of salt. 
5. If you are making crispy rosemary  have a paper towel lined plate ready. Add 2-3 tbsp olive oil to a small saucepan & place over a medium heat until the oil is hot. 
6. Drop one rosemary leaf in & wait for it to sizzle. When it sizzles the oil is ready. Add all of the rosemary leaves & cook just until they begin to curl. Remove using a fork & allow rosemary to drain on paper towel. 
7. Cook pasta according to packet instructions & drain. Add sauce to the pasta saucepan & stir through to warm. Add black pepper if you like. 
8. To serve arrange the pasta onto serving plates, drizzle with olive oil and sprinkle over bread crumbs. Finish with the crispy rosemary. 
9. *For breadcrumbs take stale bread and whizz it in food processor until you have crumbs. Or take 2 slices (loaf ends work well here) and toast in a toaster or in a low oven (100 degrees fan) for about 10 mins & then whizz.

#VEDAY75 | Victory in Europe Day, generally known as VE Day or V-E Day, is a day celebrating the formal acceptance by the Allies of World War II of Nazi Germany's unconditional surrender of its armed forces on Tuesday, 8 May 1945, marking the end of World War II in Europe. Years of carnage and destruction had come to an end and millions of people took to the streets and pubs to celebrate peace, mourn their loved ones and to hope for the future. ❤️
_______________________________________
These images serve as a reminder of not only of the sacrifices of our ancestors and grand parents, but of a time when the country united to rebuild the nation. 💪🏼 The country is urged to remember, lest we forget, and draw on the same spirit of national endeavour as we work together through the present coronavirus crisis. 🙏🏼❤️🙏🏼
_______________________________________
#WinstonChurchill said on this day 75 years ago... “Everyone has tried. Neither the long years, nor the dangers, nor the fierce attacks of the enemy, have in any way weakened the independent resolve of the British nation. God bless you all.”

MAKE FLUFFY JAPANESE PANCAKES THIS WEEKEND! 🥞💗🥰 TAG someone who needs this in their life!! 👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼
_______________________________________

INGREDIENTS FOR 4-5 PANCAKES 🥞 • 4 EGGS
• 70 GRAMS FLOUR
• 1 TABLESPOON OIL (to grease pan)
• 50 GRAMS SUGAR
• 4 TABLESPOON MILK
• 2 TEASPOONS VANILLA EXTRACT
• 1 TEASPOON BAKING POWDER
• 2 PINCHES OF SALT

_______________________________________

METHOD • First separate the egg whites and the yolks and beat the yolks.
• Add the milk to the yolks along with the vanilla extract. Mix until frothy.
• Sieve the flour and baking powder together, and add to mix.
• Add a couple of pinches of salt. Mix until combined but don’t over mix.
• Preheat a pan on a LOW heat. Meanwhile whisk the egg whites until frothy.
• Add the sugar to the egg whites a little at a time and beat until hard peaks form.
• Now add 1/3 of the egg white mix to the yolk mix and stir in slowly until all the same colour.
• Now put the yolk mix back into the rest of the egg white mix and mix with folded motions, trying not to break the air bubbles.
• Grease your pan with a little oil and pour 3 tablespoons of your mix, per pancake.
• Cover the pan and cook for 2 minutes. After 2 minutes, add another 2 tablespoons of the mix to each of your pancakes. Cover again.
• Cook for another 4 minutes, and then very carefully turn the pancakes over, and cook for a further 4 minutes, covering the pan again.
• The pancakes are done – add your favourite toppings to taste. We sieve powdered royal icing sugar over the top and add fruits such as blueberries, strawberries, clotted cream OR extra thick cream, and Golden Syrup. But feel free to freestyle! 
_______________________________________

*Any Lentil & Any Bean Chilli* to feed your street! SO EASY & it makes 10+ portions so share with your street or store in your freezer! 
___________________________________
INGREDIENTS:
450g uncooked brown/green lentils
3 x 400g mixed tins cooked beans
1 v big onion or 2 onions / leeks, diced
4 fat garlic cloves, finely chopped
1 heaped tsp dried oregano or thyme 
4 x big handfuls diced veg - carrot/peppers/celery/ courgette 
2 x 400ml tinned tomatoes + 2 tbsp tomato puree if poss
1-2 tsp maple syrup /ketchup
1.5 litres veg stock /broth (or water)
sea salt & pepper, to taste
-
SPICES - work with what you've got and amp up the levels of spices as much as you like.. I kept mine gently spiced for families.
*1.5 tbsp ground cumin or 1 heaped tbsp of cumin seeds
*Pinch chilli flakes/powder or cayenne, as hot as you like
*1 tbsp smoked paprika
-
Plus if you've got any of these….
*1 tsp ground cinnamon *2 bay leaves
___________________________________
To serve, optional:
*Homemade pink pickled onions (sliced red onion in a vinegar salt bath!)
*Quick slaw (shredded cabbage plus splash of olive oil and vinegar)
*Garlic yoghurt (yoghurt + finely chopped garlic + salt *Grated cheddar cheese
*If you have any - coriander/lime/lemon /Jalapeños
___________________________________
METHOD:
1 Melt ghee/oil in your biggest pan, add onions, fry on medium heat for 8 mins.

2. Add garlic, spices, herbs and chopped veg, stir, fry for a minute, keeping an eye on them, stirring occasionally and adding a splash of water if they start to stick.

3. Add tomatoes, lentils and stock. Bring to boil, reduce heat to medium and simmer for 15 mins, lid on. Stir every 5 mins making sure you get to the bottom of the pan so lentils don’t stick.  Add more hot water if needed.

4.  Meanwhile, make pickled onions by mixing a sliced red onion + 3 tbsp of apple cider vinegar & a pinch of sea salt. Leave to ‘pickle’. Prepare the garlic yoghurt, grate the cheese & make the slaw.

5. Then add cooked beans to the chilli for another 10 mins. Check liquid levels. If too much liquid turn up heat with lid off to thicken.

6. When veg & lentils tender season to taste, remove from heat & serve with toppings!

MAKE A KILLER WEEKEND SHAKSHUKA WITH JOHNGS! 
_______________________________________

INGREDIENTS (Serves 2)
1 tbsp Olive Oil 
1 Red Onion, finely chopped
100g Chorizo, finely chopped
1 Clove Garlic, finely chopped
4 Tomatoes, finely chopped
1 tsp Smoked Paprika
4 Free-Range Eggs
Pinch of Salt for your eggs
1 tsp Chilli Flakes
Handful of Parsley, roughly chopped
Tahini to serve
Bread / Sour Dough to serve
Sea Salt
_______________________________________

METHOD:
1. Heat the oil in a non-stick frying pan over a medium heat. Add the onion and chorizo and cook, stirring occasionally for 4-5 mins until a little golden. 
2. Add the garlic, tomatoes, smoked paprika, chilli and a good pinch of salt to the pan. Mix well and reduce heat to medium-low. Cook, stirring occasionally, for 4-5 mins until the tomatoes have broken down into a thick sauce. Add a little water to help them, if required.
3. Using the back of a spoon, make a few wells in the sauce and crack the eggs into the wells. Season the whites with salt and a tiny pinch of smoked paprika. Cooked for 6-8 mins until the whites of the eggs are set. 
4. Top Tip - now muddle the whites into the sauces with a skewer to help them. 
5. Scatter parsley over the top and drizzle over a little tahini. Serve immediate with plenty of bread. 
_______________________________________

jamieoliver introduces us to the beautiful traditional mediterranean seasoning, Harissa. This rich, spicy and flavoursome paste can turn a normal dish into something extremely special! Jamie combines the Harissa with succulent chicken, vibrant sweet peppers, red onion and tops the dish off with fresh mint. It’s a must try! 
_______________________________________
HARISSA CHICKEN TRAYBAKE

Ingredients
* 	4 mixed-colour peppers
* 	2 red onions
* 	1 x 1.2 kg whole free-range chicken
* 	4 heaped teaspoons rose harissa
* 	4 sprigs of fresh mint
_______________________________________

Method
1. Preheat the oven to 180ºC/350ºF/gas 4.

2. Deseed the peppers and tear into big chunks, peel and quarter the onions and break apart into petals, then place it all in a 30cm x 40cm roasting tray.

3. Use a large sharp knife to carefully cut down the back of the chicken, so you can open it out flat, then score the legs. Add to the tray with the harissa, and a little sea salt, black pepper and red wine vinegar. Toss well, making sure you get into all the nooks and crannies of the chicken.

4. Sit the chicken flat on top of the veg, skin side up, and roast it all for 50 minutes, or until gnarly and cooked through. Pick over the mint leaves before dishing up.

TRY HER MEXICAN NACHO PLATE! 
________________________________________
 Takes 10 mins. Great for a movie. Makes 2 portions. 
________________________________________

INGREDIENTS

240g 8½ oz) drained tinned blacked beans
1 tablespoon chilli / bbq OR fajita spice mix
1 splash of Plant Cream (or any cream)
1 Avocado, peeled and pitted
1 squeeze of lemon juice
Salt
Corn Chips, to serve
Lime Wedges, to serve (optional)

For The Fresh Salsa
300g (10½ oz) cherry tomatoes, halved
30g (1 oz) coriander (oilantro) leaves, chopped
½ shallot, finely chopped
½ chilli, chopped
1 pinch of salt and freshly cracked black pepper

________________________________________

METHOD

To make the black beans, put the drained beans in a blender with the fajita spice mix, plant cream (or any cream) and a pinch of salt and pulse until well mixed. Scoop out onto a plate and spread evenly. Next mash the avocado with the squeeze of lemon and a sprinkle of salt, and put on top of the blacked beans.

To make the salsa, put the tomato halves into a bowl and add the remaining salsa ingredients. Toss gently. 
Put a dollop of salsa on the plates, scatter the corn chips  around the edges and add some lime wedges (if available) for extra zing, if you like! Enjoy straightaway, with a movie! Enjoy!

HUMMUS CURRY!
_______________________________________

Yep, you read that right. Hummus Curry. Now before you think we’ve lost our goddamn minds, hear us out. We’ve created a beautiful new addition to our collection of chickpea-rich recipes. What can we say? We're hummus-obsessed. It sounds like it wouldn't work...but it works so well. See for yourself. 
_______________________________________

INGREDIENTS
Curry
1 tbsp coconut oil
1 large onion
1 small red chilli
2 cloves garlic
2 inches fresh ginger
1 tbsp garam masala
1/2 tsp cumin
1/2 tsp ground coriander
1/2 tsp turmeric
1/4 tsp cayenne pepper
2 tsp tomato puree
1 x 400g can chopped tomatoes
200ml water
1 x 400g can chickpeas
1 tbsp mango chutney
200g hummus
100g spinach
Salt and pepper to taste
5g coriander
To Serve
2 x 250g bag brown basmati rice
Equipment
Large pan
Grater
Colander
_______________________________________

METHOD

Prepare the ingredients. Peel and dice the onion. Trim, halve, deseed and dice the chilli. Peel and grate the garlic and ginger. Drain the chickpeas.

Start to cook. Warm the coconut oil in a pan over a medium heat. Add the onions to the pan with a pinch of salt and stir for 4-5 minutes. Add the chilli, garlic and ginger and stir for 2 minutes.

Add the spices to the pan and stir for a further 2 minutes. Add the tomato purée and stir for 1 minute. Add the chopped tomatoes to the pan, half-fill the can from the tomatoes with the water and add that to the pan to, stir to combine and simmer for 2-3 minutes.

Add the chickpeas to the pan and stir for 2 minutes. Add the mango chutney and hummus and stir for 2-3 minutes to combine. Add the spinach and fold it into the pan until well slightly wilted. 
Taste the curry and season to perfection with salt and pepper.

Serve it up! Prepare the rice according to packet instructions. Spoon the rice into the bowls, then spoon curry over the rice. Sprinkle over the coriander and serve immediately.

STORE CUPBOARD FLAPJACKS
_______________________________________

140g unsalted butter (or salted if thats all you have)
125g light brown sugar
4 tbsp golden syrup
200g rolled oats (regular rolled oats is preferable but whatever you have will work)
150g mix ins - I used 50g seeds, 50g raisins, 50g mix of chopped nuts and coconut plus a couple tbsp cocoa nibs
_______________________________________

To make the flapjacks preheat the oven to 200C (180C fan) and lightly grease a 8 inch square tin and line with parchment paper. Place the butter, sugar and golden syrup into a large saucepan and cook over medium heat until melted and smooth. 
Take the pan off the heat and add the oats and your chosen mix-ins (sticking to about 150g but using whatever you have in the cupboard, you could also just add more oats). Scrape the mixture into the prepared tin and use firm pressure to compact into an even layer. 
Bake in the preheated oven for about 20 minutes or until deep golden brown around the edges and a little paler but still golden on top. 
Remove from the oven and allow to cool to room temperature before cutting into pieces. 
Kept covered these will keep for 4-5 days.

ROSEMARY CLODAGH BREAD
_____________________________________ 
Makes 1 Loaf 
INGREDIENTS:
350g / 3 cups wholemeal flour
200g / 1 ¾ cups white flour / all purpose flour
2 teaspoons of bicarbonate of soda / bread soda
1 teaspoon of salt 
1 tablespoon of fresh rosemary, finely chopped
350ml / 1 ½ cups milk
250ml / 1 cup natural yogurt
*Note you can also use 600ml buttermilk, or 600ml of milk instead of the milk and yogurt mix
For brushing
milk and yogurt mix (for brushing) 
_____________________________________
METHOD:
1. Pre-heat the oven to 220°C, 425°F, Gas Mark 7.

2. Sieve the white flour and bicarbonate of soda and salt into a large mixing bowl,
and stir in the wholemeal flour. Using clean hands mix the flours, bread soda and finely chopped fresh rosemary together. Make a well in the centre of the bowl.

3. Whisk together the yogurt and milk and slowly pour into the well of flour. Using a fork mix the flour into the milk mixture. Make sure that there are no dry patches and that the dough is completely wet. Pat your hands with flour and shape the dough into one round. Place on a floured baking tray. Flour a large knife and cut the shape of a cross into the top of the dough about two-thirds of the way through.Brush the round of bread with the milk and yogurt mixture using a pastry brush, this will give a lovely golden colour to the bread once baked. 
4. Bake in a pre-heated oven at 200°C, 400°F, Gas Mark 6 for 20 minutes, then reduce the heat to 150°C, 350°F, Gas Mark 4 for a further 20 minutes. To test whether the loaf is cooked, tap the back with your knuckles; it should sound hollow. Leave to cool on a cooling rack.

Chicken Tikka Masala Fakeaway
___________________________________

4 chicken breasts cut into cubes
-
Salt and pepper to season
-
1 tbs olive oil
-
1 tsp black mustard seeds
-
2 onions fine chopped -
3 cloves garlic grated -
Thumb size knob of ginger grated -
2 tsp smoked paprika
-
2 tsp ground cumin
-
2 tsp ground coriander
-
2 tbs gara masala
-
1 tbs tomato puree
-
1 x 400g tin chopped tomatoes
-
350ml chicken stock
-
4 healed tbs ground almonds
-
150ml tbs single cream
-
2 tbs honey
-
Juice of 1/2 lemon
-

Heat the oil in a large non-stick saucepan over a medium heat
-

Add the mustards seeds, when the begin to pop add the onion, garlic and ginger with a good pinch of salt -
Cook over a medium heat for ten minutes until the onion begins to caramelise and turn golden brown, if it’s begins to go too dry add a splash of water. -

Add the paprika, ground cumin, ground coriander, gara masala and tomato puree to the pan and cook for a minute, keep stirring being careful not to let the spices stick to the pan and burn, add a splash of water if it begins to look to dry
-

Now add the chopped chicken breasts and give it a good stir to coat them in the spices
-
Add in the chopped tomatoes and stock, cover loosely with a lid and then reduce the heat and simmer for 20 minutes or until the chicken is cooked and the sauce has thickened, then add the ground almonds and simmer for another couple of minutes -
Stir in the cream and honey  along with the lemon juice, and scatter with coriander.

Short chat between MrLondon & his mum MoBurt1 who suffers from Pulmonary Hypertension. Today we’re taking Mo to the Royal-Free Hospital in Hampstead for a critical investigation into her lungs and heart. The procedure can’t wait. But with #COVID19 / #CoronaVirus spreading in London it’s a real risk for people like mum and we wanted to highlight the need for patience, kindness and understanding, even if the pandemic doesn’t seem real to you, or you feel fit and well and are frustrated by the gradual shut down and restrictions being imposed, it’s ultimately about the preservation of life. Thanks MoBurt1 for helping us to humanise something that is unprecedented. 🙏🏼❤️🙏🏼
________________________________________
On a practical note, if everyone knocked on the door of the neighbour to the left and the right, no-one would be left behind. People like mum need help with groceries for the next 12 weeks. Let’s use the time we have at home to be kind to our neighbours. You never know who is struggling or who might be in a similar position. Thanks everyone. ❤️ MrLondon ❤️

🔥 Something for the weekend! It’s felicityspector here checking out the fabulous new oklava_ldn Bakery in #Fitzrovia, by chef selinkiazim - she’s developed a wonderful range of #Turkish breads and baked goods along with some really delicious breakfast and all day dishes! 🙏🏼 I couldn’t resist the super-custardy French Toast covered in crunchy pistachios, served with kaymak (a kind of clotted cream) and some insanely delicious banana jam - plus the incredible warm cookie stuffed with homemade made chocolate praline - wow. 😱 We also tried the ‘full Turkish’ breakfast with soft boiled egg, feta, honey butter and fruit and veg served with a traditional sesame crusted simit bread. 👌🏼 And of course the rhubarb and custard filled pogaca, a cross between a doughnut and brioche, and very delish it is too! 🙈🙌🏼 Selin is one of London’s most talented chefs and bread really is her passion - now, after a highly popular Kickstarter campaign - she finally has a bakery-cafe to showcase it. Tag a bread-loving friend! 👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼 // #thisislondon #londonreviewed #londonlife #londonfood

For the #Londoners. The ones we lost on Friday. The ones who ran towards danger. The families. The watchers on. For everyone affected. We stand as one. MrLondon checking in for #WorldMentalHealthDay... today is all about suicide prevention and awareness. Did you know someone dies from suicide every 40 seconds? 🤷🏻‍♂️ That’s almost 800,000 people lost every year, and that’s why we need to talk about it more. 🙏🏼 I’ve personally experienced depression. And I’ve battled with anxiety for a couple of years. I’ve also had panic attacks that have been debilitating. Growing up I would never have talked about it, let alone on Instagram - I would have always tried to “man up”. 🤷🏻‍♂️ But you know what? I’m not ashamed and I’m very comfortable talking about it. In fact I love talking about it because if my story can help just ONE person to talk to a friend, a family member, or even a colleague or classmate, then it will have been worth it. 💪🏼 If you’re struggling, talk to someone. Do it tonight. Don’t suffer in silence you can find hope. You can break through. You can find light in the darkness. 💡// #thisislondon #londonlife #lovelondon #visitlondon #mrlondon #coventgarden 📸 alice.sampo ❤️

MrLondon checking in with a #LondonParks feature that blows my mind every time I watch it. AnthonyHurren filmed this stunning piece of film in Richmond on his Fuji X-T3. You’d think we were watching a David Attenborough feature about another part of the world. But no. #ThisIsLondon! 🙏🏼🤷🏻‍♂️ To have this park on our doorstep is one one of London’s greatest treasures. Built in the 17th century it today boasts more than 600 fallow deer 🦌 and almost 1,000 hectares of land. If you’re visiting London - put it on your list. Rain or sun, it’s an absolute dream. We thoroughly recommend heading down for sunrise. It’s heaven on earth. 😍 Thanks for the film AnthonyHurren 🙏🏼🙏🏼

🇬🇧morganmotor 😍Only way to ride to goodwoodrevival! 🚗💨😎 mrlondon checking in. I’ve just posted some stories from #GoodwoodRevival. It’s a historic car festival celebrating cars made between 1948 and 1966. And it takes place in the south of england in Chichester. It’s a brilliant excuse for a road trip and there’s nothing quite like it. Guests only wear clothes from the period and the entire estate is turned back in time to a golden era. Take a look - let me know what you think! 👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼 And if you’ve never been, make sure you go next year! It’s literally unmissable. // #goodwood #supercarsoflondon #thisislondon #morgan #morganplus4 #londonlife

The #CuttySark British clipper ship in #Greenwich shot by tmnikonian - stunning capture under neath the copper hull that made this the fastest ship of her kind back in 1869, right before steam propulsion took over. For 10 years she held the record for the fastest transportation of wool from Australia, beating every sailing ship by 25 days to over a month. Not bad considering she was 14 years old at this point! Tag a history friend who will appreciate a #FactForTuesday 👇🏼👇🏼 // #ThisIsLondon #LondonLife #VisitGreenwich #London #rmg

It isn’t St Paul’s taking the limelight this time... instead, have you heard of #BromptonOratory captured here by sarahjanefouracres?! 😍😱 Sitting in #Knightsbridge is this neo-classical Roman Catholic Church. Built in 1884, Brompton was a village back then, now more commonly known as #SouthKensington. This building was also once used by Soviet spies during the Cold War as a dead drop - a place to pass secret information between people and in order to communicate with Moscow! Fascinating! Thanks for the pic sarahjanefouracres 👌🏼 // #thisislondon #londonlife #london #brompton

Notting Hill Carnival history... Many people from the #Caribbean searched for a new life in the UK as part of the Windrush Generation. •
In 1959, Trinidadian #ClaudiaJones, a community activist, wanted to unite the community who migrated over.
• 
That year, Claudia held the first of several Caribbean Carnivals at St. Pancras Town Hall. It featured a ‘Carnival Cabaret’ - perhaps the first time the UK saw Caribbean carnival costumes.
•
Since her introduction of the festival, it has gone on to become an integral part of London life every August Bank Holiday. 👌🏼
•

It’s felicityspector checking out the fabulous luminarybakery in #StokeNewington - couldn’t resist a vast slice of their justly famous carrot cake - plus some lemon drizzle, a salted caramel brownie and some of their delicious soda bread with hummus and summer veg. Luminary really is a very special place - as well as a bakery and cafe, it’s a social enterprise which trains women in baking and hospitality. Many of the women who work here have been through domestic violence, homelessness, sexual exploitation or crime and the skills they learn are truly empowering and offer the opportunity of independence and  decent work. Plus - with ambassadors like henriettainman and bakedbybenji - as you can imagine the cakes, bread and buns they produce are terrific. MrLondon with a #throwback for the 160th anniversary of when #BigBen first began striking the hour - 11th July 1859. The Great Bell is actually called “Big Ben” and it forms part of the Great Clock within the #ElizabethTower, even though everyone calls the entire landmark “Big Ben”. Regardless, we all miss the tower and hope the restoration stays on track for a reveal in 2021. 🙏🏼 The conservation work has been meticulous with master craftsman and stonemasons repairing 700 pieces of stonework, and even removing and repairing the entire roof. Gilding has been restored and the clock dials and faces taken back to the original opal colour. Not long to go...! 🙏🏼😱👌🏼🇬🇧 // #tbt #thisislondon #westminster #london #londonlife

The #ChurchillArms in #NottingHill shot by bei.bei.wei! 🙏🏼❤️🙏🏼 Built in 1750 it was a regular for #WinstonChurchill’s grandparents, which led to it being renamed after World War II. Their flower displays have also won awards, they serve incredible #Thai food inside and have beautiful ales. So worth a visit! 🙏🏼 // #thisislondon #londonlife #london #londonfood.

MrLondon checking in with some #Art & #Culture | pitzhanger Manor & Gallery in #Ealing has reopened for the first time in 3 years. Home to renowned architect Sir John Soane in the 1800’s, now open to the public, it’s worth checking out the sculptures of #AnishKapoor which challenge the notion of form and space by disorientating the viewer and transforming your surroundings. Open until 18 Aug. Check pitzhanger for viewing times and tickets. MrLondon at 23 #Eastcheap - built in 1861 and now cowering under the #WalkieTalkie. Once home to Messrs.’ Hunt & Crombie. Now... Joe & The Juice 😊 Look up into the eaves and you’ll spot dogs 🐶 and pigs 🐷 heads. And on the Philpot Lane side you’ll find two little mice 🐭 fighting over a piece of cheese! 🧀 Allegedly mice were stealing the builders lunches back in the day. OR another tale goes that two builders accused each other of stealing the others lunch, when it was the mice all along, and a fight resulted in them plunging to their deaths below. 🤷🏻‍♂️ We may never know the real reason for the little mice being honoured on the side of building. But it’s something to look out for next time you pass. And all we know is... #ThisIsLondon ☺️❤️🙏🏼

👑 Did you know the #Queen has 2 birthdays? 😱 The first on April 21st is her actual birthday anniversary. She turned 93 earlier this year. But as April is usually colder she’s allowed to have her “official” birthday on the 2nd Saturday in June. Smart lady exercising a custom that is more than 250 years old! 🎂 Hence today there was the customary annual  #TroopingTheColour parade in Whitehall, followed by a flypast over #BuckinghamPalace from the RAFRedArrows - captured here by littlelondonwhispers 🎥❤️ How British is this?! 🇬🇧❤️🇬🇧 // #thisislondon #HappyBirthdayYourMajesty 👑

D-Day | #HMSBelfast | On this day, 75 year ago, 156,000 allied troops landed on the beaches of occupied #Normandy. HMS Belfast is one of only 3 bombardment vessels to survive. Casualties were treated on-board and they spent 33 days supporting the landings, firing over 4,000 6-inch and 1,000 4-inch shells. This was the last time she fired her guns in World War II. The gallant actions of British, US & Commonwealth forces secured a bridgehead that enabled the liberation of Europe from Nazi domination. Called #OperationOverlord, today it is more usually referred to as D-Day. The forces landed on five beaches, with parachute and special forces dropped in before the main assault. 
D-Day was, and remains now, the largest combined land, sea and air operation in history. By the end of the 6th of June 1944, 10,000 allied casualties had been taken. The relative stability that we have enjoyed since then is as a direct result of their sacrifice, as well of all those gave their lives to fight the forces of fascism. 
At the going down of the sun, and in the morning, we will remember them. // #DDay #DDay75 #WW2 #WorldWar2 #remember #remembrance #wewillrememberthem #lestweforget #respect #veterans #thisislondon imperialwarmuseums britisharmy 📸 mrlondon

Arts Editor Belleannee checking in with a few thoughts and these wonderful images by theliamman 🔥 || Museum and gallery exhibits worldwide are at an all-time high. But visitors interactions and dwell time with the art is quite low. Museums around the world are doing what they can to change this & several signed up to #SlowArtDay in April. Tate is actively encouraging people to spend 10 to 15 minutes looking at a single piece of art as opposed to the 15 to 30 seconds they are currently averaging. These stunning photos by theliamman really show how he’s embraced this installation called “Sol LeWitt Upside Down” by yanghaegue, and his edits serve as inspiration to stop and take the time to soak in what is in front of you and what surrounds you.  But what do you think about the slow art movement? How much time do you spend looking at art versus reading the information printed next to each piece? What do you think can be done to encourage people to linger as opposed to quickly move from piece to piece? 👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼 // #thisislondon #londonart

The wonder of #ShadThames by the talented tamemkhuram 😍 This street is literally next to #TowerBridge - we’re still convinced many people stop at the iconic bridge and fail to notice this beautiful street, just yards away, so steeped in history. It’s a 19th century warehouse complex that was the largest of its kind in London, famous for spices and tea that rolled in on “clippers”. ⛵️ Goods were moved from the river over these bridges into the warehouses. // #thisislondon #london

ioana.berbec in #Neasden... in 2000 the Guinness Book of World Records stated - The Shri Swaminarayan Temple in Neasden, London, UK, is the largest Hindu temple outside India. It was built by Pramukh Swami, a 92-year-old Indian sadhu (holy man), and is made of 2,828 tonnes of Bulgarian limestone and 2,000 tonnes of Italian marble, which was first shipped to India to be carved by a team of 1,526 sculptors. The temple cost £12 million to build. 😱 What a glorious pic. Thanks ioana.berbec 👌🏼 // #thisislondon #london

Arts & Culture editor belleannee popping in with a weekend idea for you: LeightonHouseMuseum is the former home of Lord Leighton, a celebrated British artist from the Victorian era.  His is the only purpose-built studio-house open to the public in the UK and from the outside you’d never believe what the inside holds! The museum gives an insight into the wealth, taste and status of a successful and flamboyant artist, Royal Academician and founder of the Holland Park Circle, lived 130+ years ago.  The strict no 🚫📷 rule forces you to be in the moment and take it all in.... as he undoubtedly lived his life. (And no rules were broken... Permission for these pics was graciously provided by Leighton House). Open 9-5:30 daily, closed Tuesdays.  Check the website for a ton of special events they host including drink + draw in the studio, family events and lates. // #thisislondon #londonart

Morning! It’s felicityspector here at the fabulous new mielbakery in #WarrenStreet - tucking into an amazing spread by acclaimed pastry chef Shaheen Peerbhai aka purplefoodie ... we’ve got a super flaky caramelised kouign amman, a sable Breton with pecans, a beautiful Valrhona chocolate tart and a crunchy, custardy canele warm from the oven. Plus a big cup of velvety hot chocolate... it doesn’t get much better than this! UKParliament has released an image of the newly restored and revealed North clock dial on the #ElizabethTower - otherwise known as #BigBen, you can see for the first time the real tangible difference being made by the restoration works. 😍 The old clock dials look quite tired now, when compared side-by-side with the new North dial. The other notable difference is the return to BLUE hands and numbers. Not black! 😱 This was actually the original decorative scheme but unless you were alive before 1930 you won’t have ever seen it in this scheme. Fun fact. We’re all excited to see some progress though! Are you?! 👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼 // #thisislondon #london #westminster #visitparliament #housesofparliament // 📸 © ukparliament / Mark Duffy

Arts editor belleannee here checking in with a bit of architecture & design for your arts and culture this weekend. This is spencer.house, the sumptuously designed and impeccably preserved 18th-century residence built by the first #EarlOfSpencer, an ancestor of the late #PrincessDiana. See, way back when, when a noble title was bestowed upon you, the expectation of a solid social schedule was also bestowed.  What else would a good noble Earl do besides build the most ambitious example of architecture and design of his day to host all those fabulous parties? Even back then (built 1756 -1766) the house was immediately hailed as one of the finest examples of its type and “subtle” wasn’t in the designers vocabulary.  Lucky for us it has survived 250 years intact and is available for tours (as well as private hire if you want to be nobility for the day). 🤩 // #thisislondon #london #londonart || 📸 All photos by the lovely skyeoneill - thank you! ❤️🙏🏼

MrLondon checking in. After several weeks away, thrilled to be back in the city that I love. 🇬🇧❤️🇬🇧 It’s been so good for my mental health to hide away in Italy, just detoxing and avoiding the internet in all honesty. Funny thing to do when you make your money from the internet. But I find it very helpful to reset at the end of each year and get my head straight for the year ahead. Feeling super refreshed and excited for the year ahead. This city is incredible. There’s so much opportunity here. We cannot take this great city for granted. After travelling to other nations and coming home I’m always struck by how incredible #London is. It’s good to fall in love with this city again and again. ☺️🙏🏼 Anyways. #LondonArts by belleannee:  Kicking off 2019 at the saatchi_gallery today with the VR art exhibition you have to make a resolution to visit.  From now until January 20th at #SaatchiGallery on #KingsRoad marshmallowlaserfeast
in collaboration with  natansinigaglia and milee.ce has created “We Live in an Ocean of Air” a 20-minute multi-sensory virtual reality experience that traces the inhalation and exhalation of your breath through breath and heart sensors and you watch your life create life in a forest around you.  The purpose of is to show our connection to nature and the result is fabulous and fascinating and also important.  The result is stunning!  Tickets are £20 and must be booked in advance. Enjoy. // #thisislondon #londonreviewed

MrLondon with a LEGAL photo taken from a helicopter above #TowerBridge. For anyone caught up in the #Gatwick Drone nightmare - we’re so sorry that you’ve suffered. 😕❤️ If we as a nation haven’t got a technical answer to triangulating drones - God help us. We were triangulating radio transmitters in the first and second world wars. Now we have satellites in the sky and have put a man on the moon, why we can’t deal with these drones is beyond me. 🤷🏼‍♂️ It’s a scary vulnerability that our transport hubs can be broken so easily. What I will say is that it’s about time the CAA started to make examples of the people flouting the laws. And that includes instagrammers who think it’s cool to fly above the 400ft ceiling. Its not cool. It’s unbelievably stupid. And it’s no use the CAA re-publishing guidelines and rules if you don’t enforce them. People are regularly flying drones above Tower Bridge at the same height I was flying in this helicopter. You only have to look at the recent helicopter crash in Leicester to see what happens when a helicopter comes down. We publish the work of jasonhawkes regularly, another helicopter aerial specialist photographer. There are ways to shoot these type of photos legally and professionally. But people trying to push the limits for the sake of the ‘gram are putting lives at risk and they are going to regret the day they take down a helicopter or plane taking off from any of the 3 neighbouring airports. It’s going to happen, eventually. About time CAA got a grip. 💥👊🏼💥 // #thisislondon #london #drones

Arts & Culture editor Belleannee checking in with a timely nudge: There is lots to know about global warming but sometimes it can be hard to put scientific data into something we can visualize.  Enter artists Olafur Eliasson and Minil Rosing who have installed an outdoor sculpture at Tate Modern and Bloomberg’s European HQ both in #London. It’s made of huge chunks of glacier ice from the Greenland ice sheet that had broken away and were melting into the ocean.  It is an interactive exhibit intended to make us see and feel what we only read about or hear politicians arguing about. Get there quickly, touch it.  Feel it.  Listen to it.  See it.  Watch it melt.  The exhibit will be there until the ice melts away.  #londonart #icewatchlondon || 📸 Images from studioolafureliasson & justin_sutcliffe 🙏🏼

🖼 belleannee says... Always beautiful on the outside, but it’s what’s inside that really counts. #MaddoxGallery has expanded from this first shopfront on Maddox Street to galleries in Gstaad, Los Angeles and 3 more in London.  Their curator (and managing director) James Nicholls is a hot item and is TV art critic, resident art expert for british_airways and Art Editor for The Player as well as being a patron of royalacademyarts, nationalportraitery and dulwichpicturegallery.  If something is worth knowing in the art world, he knows it.  Want to know more about art too? Don’t just take a photo of the outside....walk in and see what they have going on.  Who knows, you might just be a top customer one day. || Gorgeous 📸 taken by angelacoomey ❤️🙏🏼 || #thisislondon #london #londonart 🖼

Founder of the Japanese Buddhist movement, Nipponzan Myohoji, Guruji stated that 'Civilisation is not to kill human beings, not to destroy things, nor make war; civilisation is to hold mutual affection and to respect one another'. MrLondon checking in. I’m contemplating #ArmisticeDay as our day of remembrance draws to a close, marking 100 years since the end of World War One. My heart is full of gratitude for those that fought for the freedom I have today, especially my forefathers. Pic 1 is my Great Grandad who fought in WW1. He was blown up in France and suffered serious shrapnel wounds. An angelic soldier and comrade pulled him off the battlefield, and after being repatriated to England, he survived his injuries and went onto marry and have 4 children. He’d enlisted underage at 17. Pic number 2 is my Grandad who was taken as a prisoner of war when Singapore fell in 1942. He was caught up in the Thai/Burma railway construction known as the Death Railway, designed to take Japanese Imperial Army troops and supplies from Bangkok to Burma. One man died for every railway sleeper laid. 😔 The 3rd pic is me. 4 generations on. Walking in #RegentsPark without any fear. Today I can write this whilst eating a roast dinner surrounded by friends. Whatever may trouble me now seems to pale into insignificance. Tonight I will be watching “The Railway Man” - it’s all about the aforementioned PoW railway and stars Colin Firth & Nicole Kidman. It’s my way of reflecting upon my family’s own sacrifices, at a time when the entire nation reflects on many conflicts, many lives lost, many sacrifices made. My heart is full of gratitude and my prayers are that those in modern day conflict would know peace. Lots of love to everyone. #LestWeForget 🇬🇧❤️🇬🇧 // #thisislondon #london #rememberanceday #ww1 #ww2

The giant poppy at #KingsCross snapped by littlelondonwhispers 🌺 Today is #RemembranceDay and Millions of people are gathering around the UK to remember the war dead on #ArmisticeDay which marks 100 years since the end of World War One, on 11 November 1918. The nation will fall silent at 11:00 GMT to mark the war's end on the 11th hour of the 11th day of the 11th month. Big Ben's renovations were paused ahead of Armistice Day to allow the bell to chime before and after the traditional two minutes of silence at 11:00. 🇬🇧❤️🇬🇧 // #lestweforget #london #thisislondon

The installation #BeyondTheDeepeningShadow captured by pli.panda 🙏🏼 The #TowerOfLondon installation will be open to the public until Remembrance Sunday on November 11. A total of 10,000 torches have been lit in the Tower of London's dry moat every day this week. 🕯 
The nation is marking the 100th anniversary of the end of the First World War. The Queen and senior members of the Royal Family are due to attend the Festival of Remembrance at London's Royal Albert Hall on Saturday night as the 100th anniversary of Armistice Day draws nearer. 
#thisislondon #lestweforget #london 🇬🇧❤️🇬🇧

A slice of history... #GuyFawkes night or “Bonfire Night” is when Brits gather under firework lit skies to watch dummies burn on bonfires! 🔥 Why?! 🤷🏼‍♂️ It’s actually the anniversary of an attempt to blow up the #HousesOfParliament - known as the Gunpowder Plot. The dummies - or Guy - refer to Guy Fawkes who was part of the plot. Back in 1605 the plan was to blow up King James I and his government! England was Protestant. The plotters were Catholic. 36 barrels of explosive gunpowder were hidden in the cellars of parliament, but the king’s supporters got hold of a letter warning a friend to stay away from the Houses of Parliament on the 5th November. The plotters were tumbled and subsequently executed. The plot was immortalised in a nursery rhyme “Remember, remember, the fifth of November, gunpowder, treason and plot...” // Have a wonderful evening everyone! 📸 tmnikonian 🔥 // #thisislondon #london #bonfirenight #fireworks 🇬🇧❤️🇬🇧

Arts & Culture editor belleannee here with two great #London art stories for you.  The first is that of theunitlondon, a contemporary art gallery in the heart of #Mayfair run by Joe Kennedy and Jonathan Burt.  Joe and Johnathan met in secondary school in West London and are now twentysomethings pushing and kicking the artworld into the 21st century.  From how they find artists as well as buyers (social media) to the super warm welcome that greets you when you visit their gallery, the partners pride themselves on doing things a new way.  They are just packing up 21st Century Women, a show curated by and featuring top female movers in the art world including anne_morris_studio (this is the second London story I have for you). Anne is a British artist whose multimedia creations are are much loved by brands, collectors and critics.  She is an illustrator, a sculpture, a painter…. a you name it.  And these tall sculptures are my new favourites.  Don’t you want to stare and them and touch them and play with them?  Is there any better art than one that makes you desperate to feel it?  Thank you to theunitlondon for the shot of anne_morris_studio’s studio and if you have a chance to pop into Unit today you will catch the last day of the 21 Century Women exhibit.  Otherwise keep an eye on their IG account for what is coming next. // #thisislondon #london #londonart #unitlondon

#IGotLondonSkills | The #ThamesBarrier by ottoberkeley 🌊  Did you know it prevents most of Greater London from being flooded by exceptionally high tides and storm surges moving up from the North Sea? It has been operational since 1984 and cost over £500m to build. When needed, it is closed (raised) during high tide; at low tide it can be opened to restore the river's flow towards the sea. Clever eh. 🤷🏻‍♂️ || #thisislondon #london #londonreviewed

DaveBurt checking with a #STAGESIDE review // gregholden performed last night. // LIVE Stream & Stories are up! // Love this guy. So much respect for his music and songwriting. His songs got me through tough times, and he is immensely brave in tackling subjects that most people wouldn’t want to touch. In amongst all the chaos of commercial music, is there a more honest song writer? 🤷🏻‍♂️ Latest single “The Power Shift” ~ actually a big FU at Trump ~ reflects on the modern world and the rabbit hole we’ve all been led down. “We see your b*llshit, all of it, I hope you’re ready for a power shift”. I think we’re in crazy days, and people at large are rejecting leaders & institutions who fail, lie, who deceive, and don’t align with global values. Grab the track on apple / Spotify etc and follow gregholden for the foreseeable. Cos he’s one of the good ones. 👊🏼❤️🙏🏼🎧🇬🇧 || #thisislondon #london #gregholden #londonmusic #londonreviewed 📷 aaronparsonsphotography

The #Queen and members of theroyalfamily watched an incredible display which included the #Spitfire and new F-35 fighters. The rafredarrows brought up the rear. Arts Editor belleannee checking in with your must-see for the week:  World-renowned artist christojeanneclaude has finally unveiled his newest work #LondonMastaba ... It’s a stand-alone sculpture of 7,506 ... 55-gallon oil barrels floating in #SerpentineLake in #HydePark (no small feat for a 650 ton installation). He self-funds his gargantuan projects through the sale of his art, some of which is on display at the serpentineuk.  This project is estimated to cost 4.2m and has been in the works since October 2016.  And, it's amazing. So go see it! 🙌🏼💗 || #londonreviewed #thisislondon #londonart || Photos by wolfgangvolz christojeanneclaude & daveburt 👌🏼

Art & Culture Editor belleannee checking in... The Royal National Theatre in London (aka National Theatre of Great Britain) is another stunning example of #Brutalist architecture.  #PrinceCharles, perhaps not a fan, described the building in 1988 as, “a clever way of building a nuclear power station in the middle of #London without anyone objecting.” 😂👌🏼 Regardless of your aesthetic preferences, the NT is a spectacular addition to Great Britain’s dedication to the arts.  It contains three separate theatres as well as a forecourt used for open-air performances in the summer.  If you are a budding (or established) theatre aficionado and want to learn more, the foyers are open to the public as well as bookshops, restaurants and bars (and a well loved espresso bar!) There are also backstage tours and courses teaching playwriting and technical skills on offer. 🇬🇧❤️🇬🇧 || 📸 Fabulous photographs by josephowen ❤️ || #thisislondon #londonreviewed #londonart

Food Editor ClerkenwellBoyEC1 says "A huge congratulations to the talented & wonderful Claire of violetcakeslondon for creating the STUNNING cake for #PrinceHarry and #MeghanMarkle's #RoyalWedding". Claire started her business as a stall holder selling cakes on #BroadwayMarket, #EastLondon, cooking from home, before opening her organic bakery in 2010. 
What a fairy tale it must be to create such a special cake for the #RoyalFamily. 
In a break from tradition the centerpiece was split into three pieces and each placed upon a golden throne.

The royal wedding cake has been made from 200 Amalfi lemons, 10 bottles of #Sandringham elderflower cordial, 20kg of butter, 20kg of sugar and 500 organic eggs from Suffolk.

The inside consists of layered lemon sponge that’s been drizzled with an #elderflower syrup and sandwiched using buttercream and lemon curd, while the outside has been decorated using a white buttercream made from elderflower Swiss meringue.

Prince Harry and Meghan Markle have been heavily involved in the culinary process, with the lemon sponge made especially for the couple and the elderflower cordial made from elderflowers sourced from the #Queen’s Sandringham estate.

Violet Bakery's tasty cakes are sold at her bakery & also at Broadway Market on Saturdays from 9am to 4pm. 
#thisislondon #londonfood #londonreviewed

This week we are supporting #DeafAwarenessWeek (DAW). We want to raise awareness of #deaf people in the UK and highlights perceptions that are made of hearing loss and deafness across the UK so make sure you also watch our stories.👂 It is the third most common disability in the world but it is also the most hidden. There are about 9 million people in the UK who are deaf or hard of hearing. Technology has evolved incredibly, so today we are sharing ways that you can become Deaf confident by teaching you basic signs you can learn and use to start conversations with a deaf person. 👌🏼 We can all work together in a more inclusive society and do little things that make a big difference to deaf people, minimising their everyday challenges. Watch our stories to see our Automotive Editor masterkrishan teach you signs! 👌🏼 Thanks to lingoingcom and insignlanguage for supporting! Make sure you check them out for more! ❤️🙌🏼 || #thisislondon #londonreviewed

DaveBurt checking in at the start of #MentalHealthAwarenessWeek. 🙏🏼❤️ Did you know over the past year 3 out of 4 of us experienced #stress to the point of being overwhelmed or being unable to cope? I’m here to say that was me too. 🙌🏼 Last year was the toughest year of my life. Honestly. I still got up everyday and went to work, and I’ve never lost my love, excitement or drive. But that doesn’t mean it was easy and I experienced some tough moments. 👊🏼 I LOVE what I get to do everyday and I LOVE how we get to celebrate London together, BUT behind all my Instagram work there is a guy who has struggled with lots of everyday stuff just like others. Just like you. Which is why I am very passionate that people with influence, particularly on platforms like Instagram, should try and keep it real, help break down walls and demystify mental health. 🧠 I also want to encourage those who haven’t said anything yet, to talk to someone about it. No matter what it is. ❤️ Actually 2018 is a turning point for me and I want to call out family, friends and colleagues for the way they’ve supported me without judgement. I’ve learned a lot of life lessons and how to let go of disappointments and things I can’t change or control. 🙂 But I also want to call on YOU to be more empathetic, more supportive and implore you to find out more about Mental Health this week. Because it will affect you or someone you know in the next 12 months. Lots of love. DaveBurt ❤️ || #thisislondon #londonreviewed #MentalHealth mentalhealthfoundation

Arts Editor belleannee checking in with your gardening goals for the weekend.  If you feel like your green thumb isn’t quite up to the challenge - head to barbicancentre instead, a multi disciplinary arts center in one of the most famous examples of brutalist architecture in #London.  In addition to a packed schedule of performances and programming, the building also boasts the second largest conservatory in London, the Barbican Conservatory.  The space is home to over 2000 species of plants and trees but is only for tours and / or tea on select Sundays and bank holidays - so book in advance. 🇬🇧❤️😱🌱 || Incredible 📷 by iamlaurajackson 💕 || #thisislondon #londonreviewed #barbican

#LondonArt | belleannee checking in... Tucked neatly in-between #OxfordStreet, #BakerStreet and #Marlebone Village is, quite possibly, the best museum you’ve never heard of. wallacemuseum - a collection of four generations of really wealthy hoarders - is housed in a building that has, in its 230 year life, been a weekend house, Spanish embassy, French embassy and art Gallery.  #RichardWallace (b.1818-d.1890), the 4th Marquess’ illegitimate son, landed here when he fled Paris during the Paris Commune (two months of radical socialists ruling Paris in 1871) and sought shelter for himself and his art in his father’s #London digs.  He lived there until his death and then his wife gave it all up to London for your viewing pleasure. You’ve got to see it to believe it. 😱 (Contains a pretty great sun drenched courtyard restaurant too!) || 📸 by the lovely rebeccahope || #thisislondon #londonreviewed

#BestBurger | daveburt out with clerkenwellboyec1 to try cngburgers who picked up National Burger Of The Year Award 2018 🥇 Wonderful values behind the sourcing of their meat and ingredients. 🙏🏼 Award-winning burger and triple-cooked fries for £10. Halloumi fries + mint + yogurt 👌🏼 Vegans can enjoy the miso glazed aubergine burger. There’s a veggie halloumi + red pepper + hummus burger. And a chicken. 👌🏼🔥 Pair with a cracking pilsner 🍻 Well-deserved win. Highly recommend. Just north of #KingsCross. Off you go! 🍔😂 || #thisislondon #londonreviewed #londonfood

#LondonArt || belleannee checking in... turns out there’s some benefits to being Millennials…. Tate is is trying to reach you.  Launching today - £5 exhibition tickets for 16-25 year olds as part of new program called #TateCollective.  Register on your phone (no fee) walk up to the front desk and you + 3 friends (also under 25) get in for £5 each. 🙌🏼🔥 In Photos: Artists Will Dean (18), Gaby Sahhar (25) and Angela Wereko-Anderson (24), all part of Tate Collective, advocates for lower priced tickets and the initiative to involve young people in shaping Tate for today and tomorrow. || #thisislondon #londonreviewed

Arts Editor belleannee checking in with a must-see-exhibit for anyone who dreams of capturing that elusive photo of real life that is raw, unscripted, real.  All Too Human - on until 27 August - at tate features painted portraits by 20 or so artists, many of whom are or were London-based.  Their use of colours, textures, mediums and light present a considerably raw explosion of talent and subject that will leave you energised and driven to let authenticity reign supreme in your own photography. Even though these are all paintings the imagery is excitingly real.  Funny story - the woman featured in the painting on the left grew up in St Albans, Hertfordshire and has only just retired as a benefits supervisor.  The oil panting of her by #LucienFreud last changed hands for a cool £35million. (Top tip: go in search of Paula Rego’s “The Family” and read about it.  Try to keep a dry eye.) || #thisislondon #londonreviewed #Londonart #tate #tatebritain || 📸 Fab photo by thingsizzyloves 💕
